    "# 2. Model Training\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we train our \"Anchor\" model. This model represents the state of the world at time $t$ (the Training period).\n",
    "We will later see how its explanations \"drift\" when applied to time $t+1$ (the Test period).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Strategy:**\n",
    "1.  **Algorithm:** XGBoost Classifier (Gradient Boosting is standard for tabular fraud data). Based on results of other people (Kaggle), this algorithm performs well for this dataset.\n",
    "2.  **Imbalance Handling:** We use `scale_pos_weight` to penalize missing frauds. This is preferred over SMOTE/Undersampling for XAI stability research because it preserves the original data distribution (which we want to explain!). We try out different settings:\n",
    "-  **Undersample**: Reduce Majority class (Legit)\n",
    "-  **Oversample (SMOTE)**: Increase Minority class (Fraud) by creating synthetic examples.\n",
    "-  **Hybrid (Both)**:\n",
    "    *   First, SMOTE Fraud up\n",
    "    *   Then, Undersample Legit\n",
    "    *   *Goal:* Clean, balanced-ish dataset with synthetic variety.\n",
    "- A model that uses 'scale_pos_weight' without any imbalance handling is also trained for comparison.\n",
    "3.  **Evaluation:** We focus on AUPRC (Area Under Precision-Recall Curve) as ROC-AUC can be misleading for highly imbalanced data.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also train a baseline model that does not take time into account (data is shuffled). This can be used as a baseline for comparison. This baseline handles class imbalance using 'scale_pos_weight' as well."
   ]
  },
