    "# 7. Conclusions & Findings\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7.1 Stability Analysis\n",
    "*   **Global Stability is High ($\\rho \\approx 0.95$):** The model generally relies on the same set of features across days. The core logic of fraud detection remains consistent.\n",
    "*   **Top-End Instability ($Jaccard \\approx 0.67$):** The \"Elite\" features (Top-5) shuffle significantly. This suggests that while the broad logic is stable, the specific features used to catch the *most critical* frauds change from Day 1 to Day 2.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7.2 Circadian Rhythms (The \"Night Watchman\" Effect)\n",
    "Our temporal SHAP traces reveal that the model is **context-aware**:\n",
    "*   **V14:** Its importance spikes at ~2:00 AM. The model learns to rely heavily on V14 during low-volume night hours.\n",
    "*   **V12:** Its impact flips sign (Negative $\\leftrightarrow$ Positive) between Day and Night. This proves the model has learned complex, non-linear interactions between transaction features and time.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7.3 Model Performance & Recommendations\n",
    "*   **The Gap (Train 0.99 vs Test 0.77):** The model generalizes poorly to Day 2. This, combined with the shifting SHAP values, suggests that the **type** of fraud might be changing (Concept Drift), or the model is over-optimizing for Day 1's specific time-of-day mix.\n",
    "*   **Recommendation 1 (Explicit Time):** The strong circadian dependence suggests we should explicitly include `Hour` as a feature, rather than forcing the model to infer it from transaction stats.\n",
    "*   **Recommendation 2 (Temporal Ensembling):** Since the decision logic (SHAP signs) flips at night, training separate \"Day\" and \"Night\" models could improve stability and performance."
   ]
